Greek Stocks; Alpha Bank, Eurobank, National Bank Move in Athens

-- B y   T o m   S t o u k a s
-- 
2011-02-21T15:46:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-21/alpha-bank-eurobank-national-bank-greek-stock-market-preview.html
  Greece ’s benchmark ASE Index dropped
46.88, or 2.7 percent, to 1,668.25 at the 5:20 p.m. close in
Athens, the biggest decline in more than a week.  The FTSE/ASE 20 Index of the country’s biggest companies
slid 3.1 percent to 784.57. The Cyprus General Market Index
tumbled 6 percent to 1,240.51.  The following shares were the most active in Athens trading
today. Symbols are in parentheses.  Alpha Bank SA (ALPHA GA) rallied 5 percent to 5.03 euros,
its third day of gains. Greece’s third-biggest bank rejected an
unsolicited 2.8 billion-euro ($3.8 billion) takeover bid from
National Bank of Greece SA (ETE GA), the nation’s largest
lender. National Bank shares gained 0.4 percent to 7.60 euros.    EFG Eurobank Ergasias SA  (EUROB GA), Greece’s second
largest lender, tumbled 8.8 percent to 4.80 euros after surging
17 percent the previous trading day.  Piraeus Bank SA  (TPEIR GA)
shares lost 10 percent to 1.68 euros, paring a gain of 15
percent from Feb. 18.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Tom Stoukas in Athens at 
